rom ultimately unanswerable questions about authorship and urtext, Gregory turns instead to the editor-publishers who shaped the novel by crafting their own print editions. By examining the novel in its various incarnations, Bandits in Print shows that print is not only a stabilizing force on literary texts; in particular circumstances and with particular genres, the print medium can be an agent of textual change.  afunded by Geis Foundation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese fictionxPublishingzChinaxHistory. 0aChinese fictionyMing dynasty, 1368-1644xHistory and criticism. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  ahistory of the chinese novel, Ming Dynasty literature, four classic novels of china, Water Margin meaning, vernacular Mandarin novels.2 aGeis Foundationefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501769214zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501769214zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501769214/original  a978-3-11-075183-3 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA